in": 387, "end": 408}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004997"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "17-ethinyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9927966594696045, "span": {"begin": 410, "end": 420}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9963390827178955, "span": {"begin": 421, "end": 430}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000077300"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bosentan", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994637370109558, "span": {"begin": 432, "end": 440}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000077288"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "troglitazone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993453621864319, "span": {"begin": 442, "end": 454}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005905"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glibenclamide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993519186973572, "span": {"begin": 459, "end": 472}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8647"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BSEP", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9869928359985352, "span": {"begin": 627, "end": 631}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001647"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bile acids", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988199472427368, "span": {"begin": 650, "end": 660}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005999"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glycochenodeoxycholic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9978249073028564, "span": {"begin": 670, "end": 696}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hepatocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7858980298042297, "span": {"begin": 733, "end": 744}}], "text": "The BSEP transporter protein is a prominent adenosine triphosphate-binding cassette transporter located at the canalicular pole of the hepatocyte membrane, which conveys bile acids from the hepatocyte cytosol into the bile canaliculi (Kis et al., 2012). BSEP can be directly cis-inhibited in a competitive way by several cholestasis-inducing drugs, including cyclosporine A, rifampicin, erythromycin estolate, 17-ethinyl estradiol, bosentan, troglitazone and glibenclamide (Dawson et al., 2011; Kis et al., 2012; Morgan et al., 2010; Padda et al., 2011; Wagner et al., 2009; Zollner and Trauner, 2006 and 2008). As a result of BSEP inhibition, toxic bile acids, such as glycochenodeoxycholic acid, accumulate into the cytosol of the hepatocytes or bile canaliculi into so-called bile plugs (Kuntz and Kuntz, 2008).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:30:49 +0000 2026"}